    en: "Real Property Actions and Proceedings Law Article 15 (RPAPL 1501-1541) lets a property owner sue to clear 'clouds' on title — competing claims or ambiguities that make the property hard to sell, refinance, or insure. Common clouds: old mortgages that should have been satisfied but were not released, abandoned easements, clerical deed errors, claims by unknown heirs, adverse-possession claims, or disputed boundary lines. The plaintiff serves all potentially interested parties and obtains a judgment declaring the true state of title. A quiet title judgment cures the defect and allows clean title insurance. Service on unknown or missing parties proceeds via service by publication under CPLR 316. The judgment binds all notified parties."
