    en: "A Greece homeowner inherited a small cottage from his grandmother in 2015. The cottage had been in the family since 1948. When he attempted to sell in 2023, the title search revealed a 1962 mortgage — taken out by his grandfather, paid off by his grandmother in 1971 — that had no recorded satisfaction. The lender had been a small savings-and-loan that merged into a defunct bank in 1984. The title insurance company refused to insure without discharge of the mortgage. Since no successor lender existed to file a simple satisfaction, the homeowner filed a quiet title action in Monroe County Supreme Court naming 'unknown successors in interest to [defunct bank]' as John Doe defendants. Notice was published in a local newspaper per court order for six consecutive weeks (CPLR 316). No one appeared. At a hearing six months after filing, the plaintiff proved the grandmother had paid off the mortgage (bank records, canceled checks), and the court entered judgment declaring the mortgage discharged and title clear. The judgment was recorded; title insurance issued; the sale closed three weeks later at $280,000. Total cost: approximately $7,500 in legal fees, court fees, and publication costs."
